{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516253"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:40:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:40:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12592"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12592"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.15,0.33,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5085"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50929"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5085"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12592"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36163"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8492"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8837"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14504"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42784"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50929"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman is brought to the Emergency Department (ED) by her friend after she was found unconscious at home. The patient\u0027s friend reports that the patient has a history of major depressive disorder and was recently prescribed medication by her treating psychiatrist. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient is drowsy but rousable to pain. Her airway is patent and vital signs demonstrate her blood pressure is 100/70 mmHg, pulse 90/min and respiratory rate of 9/min, with a mild hypercapnia of PaCO2 55mmHg on venous blood gas.  An ECG shows normal sinus rhythm. Her pupils are 4 mm and reactive to light, there is shallow breathing and her reflexes are diminished. There are no visible signs of trauma or injury. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBrain imaging is unremarkable and the rest of her electrolytes and glucose are within normal range. The ED pharmacist reports that the patient last filled her prescription of lorazepam two days ago.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flumazenil","Naloxone","Supportive care","Activated charcoal","Whole bowel irrigation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the patient\u0027s presentation, polypharmacy overdose mainly affecting the CNS should be suspected. In this case, examination findings of depressed CNS with recent prescription of benzodiazepines may suggest that benzodiazepine overdose is most likely, particularly when pupils are not pinpoint and brain imaging and venous gas results are unremarkable. Benzodiazepines are commonly prescribed for anxiety and insomnia, and their overdose can cause central nervous system depression, respiratory depression and even coma. Patients who are prescribed benzodiazepines for anxiety may take more than the prescribed dose during times of increased stress and this can lead to toxicity. \u003Cstrong\u003ESupportive care\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred initial management strategy for any patient with suspected polypharmacy overdose, including benzodiazepines, who are otherwise medically stable and maintaining their own airway. Supportive care includes ensuring a clear airway, providing supplemental oxygen, monitoring vital signs, and administering intravenous fluids as needed to maintain blood pressure and prevent dehydration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlumazenil \u003C/strong\u003Eis a benzodiazepine antagonist that can reverse the effects of benzodiazepine overdose. However, it is not routinely used as a first-line management option for benzodiazepine poisoning due to the risk of seizures and worsening of symptoms in patients with physical dependence on benzodiazepines. It could be used if the patient\u0027s airway was compromised and there was not immediate access to intubation facilities. Supportive care is the preferred initial management strategy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaloxone \u003C/strong\u003Eis a medication that is used to reverse the effects of opioids. It is not the most preferred management strategy in this patient\u0027s presentation because the overall clinical picture did not suggest strongly of opioid overdose. Some of the findings that makes opioid toxicity less likely include lack of pinpoint pupils and a recent prescription history of benzodiazepines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivated charcoal \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Ewhole bowel irrigation\u003C/strong\u003E are usually used in cases of drug overdoses to absorb and remove the remaining drug from the GI tract, but they have no role in the management of a case of benzodiazepine overdose.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Supportive care of a patient is the treatment of choice in patients presenting with benzodiazepine overdose.","Flumazenil can also be used but is controversial and can cause serious side effects."],"references":["Long N. Benzodiazepine toxicity [Internet]. Life in the Fast Lane \u2022 LITFL. 2020 [cited 2023May1]. Available from: https://litfl.com/benzodiazepine-toxicity/","Kang M, Galuska MA, Ghassemzadeh S. Benzodiazepine Toxicity. [Updated 2022 Jun 27]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482238/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36163"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12592"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36163"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-18T22:29:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-14T21:05:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5085"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50929"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"em